How is this better than a simple  

return MainAsync(args).Result;  

? This would mean the ThreadPool would be used for running continuations, but I don't see any problems with that. Is the AsyncContext there really just to save one thread?

Hi,   

I was playing around with the AsyncContext, and suddenly, got into a situation which I couldn't explain. I've written a simple example below. All the tasks below seemed to execute as expected, until I put in the Console.ReadKey there. It seems the tasks complete, only when the AsyncContext ends. Am I missing something?  

 public class Program  
 {  
 private static ThreadLocal _localStr =  
 new ThreadLocal(() => String.Format("Hello from Thread: {0}!", Thread.CurrentThread.ManagedThreadId));  

 private static void Main(string[] args)  
 {  
 Nito.AsyncEx.AsyncContext.Run(() =>  
 {  

 Console.WriteLine(_localStr);  

 Task.Factory.StartNew(() => Console.WriteLine(_localStr), CancellationToken.None,  
 TaskCreationOptions.None, TaskScheduler.FromCurrentSynchronizationContext());  

 Task.Factory.StartNew(() => Console.WriteLine(_localStr), CancellationToken.None,  
 TaskCreationOptions.None, TaskScheduler.FromCurrentSynchronizationContext());  

 Task.Delay(100).Wait();  

 Console.WriteLine(_localStr);  

 Console.ReadKey();  
 });  
 }  
 }

What about WinForms?

It has a bug. When I use async Task Main I get MTA thread, instead of STA:

[STAThread]
private static async Task Main()
{
    // get MTA thread
    Thread thread = Thread.CurrentThread;
}

It gives issues when using OpenFileDialog, for example.
